Titanic Data Cleaning and Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) Project

Project Overview

This project demonstrates data cleaning and exploratory data analysis using Python, Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, and Seaborn. The dataset used is the Titanic dataset from Kaggle.

Steps Performed

1. Import Libraries

In[26]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Configure visualizations

In[27]:
%matplotlib inline
sns.set(style="darkgrid")

Load Titanic dataset from GitHub

In[28]:
url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/datasciencedojo/datasets/master/titanic.csv"

Fill missing values in 'Age' with the median age

In[33]:
df['Age'] = df['Age'].fillna(df['Age'].median())

Fill missing values in 'Embarked' with the most common port

In[34]:
df['Embarked'] = df['Embarked'].fillna(df['Embarked'].mode()[0])
In[35]:
# Drop 'Cabin' column if it exists
In[36]:
if 'Cabin' in df.columns:
    df = df.drop(columns=['Cabin'])

Remove duplicate rows if any

In[37]:
df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

Visualize the distribution of ages

In[39]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(df['Age'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Age Distribution')
plt.show()

Countplot of survivors

In[40]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.countplot(x='Survived', data=df)
plt.title('Survival Count')
plt.show()

Boxplot of age by survival status

In[41]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='Survived', y='Age', data=df)
plt.title('Age Distribution by Survival Status')
plt.show()

Select only numeric columns for correlation

In[42]:
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

Select only numeric columns for correlation

In[43]:
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

Correlation heatmap

In[44]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(numeric_df.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', linewidths=0.5)
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap')
plt.show()

Pairplot to visualize relationships between numerical variables

In[45]:
sns.pairplot(df, hue='Survived', vars=numeric_df.columns, diag_kind='kde')
plt.show()
